          <p class='first-para'>
            I thank my hon. Friend for that helpful point. In my experience, when we discuss COSAC countries, we do so with other member states. Member
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_336wh' title='Col. 336WH &mdash; HC Deb 30 January 2003 vol 398 c336WH' name='column_336wh' href='#column_336wh' rel='bookmark'>336WH</a>
            states with PR sometimes look in envy at the UK system, which produces a majority Government. Many would like a system better than their own.</p><p>
            I joined the Select Committee on European Legislation two years after the hon. Member for Stone (Mr. Cash). I met Mr. Andreotti in 1989, when he was the Italian President, although I do not know where he is now, or whether he is in prison yet. He had been an elected Member of Parliament since 1946 and, some 40 years later, had been in every Government during those years&#x2014;there had been 53 elections. That is a fairly strong point against PR, but I do not want to concentrate too much on that aspect. I feel that I have given it fair coverage.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
